@breznak Yes, it's making sure that the two match. If the Python seed dafaults to zero as well, those TM unit tests will require updating. And consequently the C++ ones change to match. I agree that this can be made more elegant by adopting zero seed across the board, and updating individual tests that expect a certain random seed.

I'll close this PR for now. Another can be raised, or handled in your PR, to cover changes required in the C++ when the Python seed gets defaulted to zero.

