@jbrandstetter yes, that would be possible, too. But this could also lead to a way more confusing situation when smb tries to configure a stack using both json and hocon configuration files at the same time. I think this would not work reliably in all situations and I do not see a good way to fence against it.

@Dgadavin this is not how pip i.e. the gcdt plugin mechanism works. Once a plugin is defined as a dependency you can not "override" it with another plugin. With pip additional dependencies are added. The situation you describe really would mean that you have two plugins installed with conflicting functionality. 
The std. installation you describe should be covered by a "std" `requirements_gcdt.txt` file. I hope that your getting started guide helps to better explain that.

Somehow it appears to be difficult to consistently maintain a list of 7 plugins :(

Something else that I thought about here is that `take_ownership` on a function returning a container pointer doesn't do what I'd expect (it acts like `reference`).

I tried extending the TYPE_CASTER macro pointer `cast()` to:
```C++
if (policy == return_value_policy::take_ownership) {
    handle h = cast(std::move(*src), policy, parent);
    delete src;
    return h;
} else {
    return cast(*src, policy, parent);
}
```
i.e. to destroy if a pointer-returning method is called with `take_ownership`, but it seems it's too late: `automatic` gets also converted into `take_ownership` before it ends up in the cast(), but we have tests expecting that a pointer return for a non-registered class doesn't get destroyed.  One possible approach is to remove the code that changes `automatic` to `take_ownership` for a pointer, so that type casters can interpret `automatic` in different ways--here, for example, it would make more sense for the default (i.e. `automatic`) to work more like `automatic_reference`.  I'm not sure how much *that* approach would break, however.

